\*[SUP]22\*[SUPX]Having therefore obtained help of God, I continue unto this day, witnessing both to small and great, saying none other things than those which the prophets and Moses did say should come:
\*[SUP]23\*[SUPX]That Christ should suffer, and that he should be the first that should rise from the dead, and should shew light unto the people, and to the Gentiles.
\*[SUP]24\*[SUPX]And as he thus spake for himself, Festus said with a loud voice, Paul, thou art beside thyself; much learning doth make thee mad.
\*[SUP]25\*[SUPX]But he said, I am not mad, most noble Festus; but speak forth the words of truth and soberness.
\*[SUP]26\*[SUPX]For the king knoweth of these things, before whom also I speak freely: for I am persuaded that none of these things are hidden from him; for this thing was not done in a corner.
\*[SUP]27\*[SUPX]King Agrippa, believest thou the prophets? I know that thou believest.
\*[SUP]28\*[SUPX]Then Agrippa said unto Paul, Almost thou persuadest me to be a Christian.
\*[SUP]29\*[SUPX]And Paul said, I would to God, that not only thou, but also all that hear me this day, were both almost, and altogether such as I am, except these bonds.
\*[SUP]30\*[SUPX]And when he had thus spoken, the king rose up, and the governor, and Bernice, and they that sat with them:
\*[SUP]31\*[SUPX]And when they were gone aside, they talked between themselves, saying, This man doeth nothing worthy of death or of bonds.
\*[SUP]32\*[SUPX]Then said Agrippa unto Festus, This man might have been set at liberty, if he had not appealed unto Caesar.
